share.share_text: White Otter Castleâ¦ Surrounded by natural beauty and steeped in legend, itâs truly a gem of the north that not many are able to experience. Jimmy McOuat constructed this three story log castle entirely on his own in the early 1900âs, at the age of 51, when there was no road access for hundreds of kilometres. Some of the red pine beams in the castle weighed up to 1600lbs, all painstaking hoisted into place. In 1918 Jimmy was found by local forest rangers, tangled in a fishing net, drowned at the bottom White Otter Lake near a reed bed, not too far from the castle. No one really knows what happened to him, but there are many rumours assuming the cause of death was not sheer accident. Now, his grave site lay next to the castle, and some say Jimmy still walks upon the grounds from time to time. If you look closely, you just might see him. @OntarioTravel #ontario_partner

Roslin Castle by @roanlavery dates back to the early 14th century, when the Sinclair family, Earls of Caithness and Barons of Roslin, fortified the site. It is situated on a rocky promontory near the site of the Battle of Roslin, where the Scots defeated the English in 1303.
â«ï¸
Roslin was severely damaged by the Earl of Hertford, who burned the castle during the War of the Rough Wooing in 1544. It was during this time that King Henry VIII tried to secure the marriage of his son, Edward, to the infant Mary, Queen of Scots (unsuccessfully). The castle was soon after rebuilt, and Mary herself stayed on 31 August 1563 during her tour of the south west of Scotland.
â«ï¸
In 1650 Roslin Castle was attacked by the artillery of Cromwellâs commander in Scotland, General Monck. It was further damaged by a reforming mob in 1688. By the 18th century the structure was dilapidated, though part of the east range has always remained habitable.
â«ï¸
From 1982 to 1988 the east range was restored by architects Simpson and Brown. The current owner, the Earl of Rosslyn, a descendant of the Sinclairs, leases the castle as holiday accommodation via the Landmark Trust.
